commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

commits.message:
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.

commits.message:
feat: Ubuntu Insights integration (#33)

This PR implements Ubuntu Insights integration with `wsl-setup` and
introduces a number of workflow tests along with it.

## Implementation
All steps are done at the end of the `wsl-setup` script, meaning that
cloud-init and users creation would have already been completed.

`ubuntu-insights` is added as a recommended dependency. If the CLI tool
can't be found, then we skip all following integration sections.

### Consent
Next, we check if at least one non-root user already has the *wsl_setup*
consent configuration set to a valid value. This could be done via
cloud-init or any other method of creating files and running commands.
If there is one, then we also skip all further consent steps.

Next, we utilize interop to check the registry key
`HKCU:\Software\Canonical\Ubuntu` value `UbuntuInsightsConsent`. If it
exists and is valid, either 0 or 1, then we use that as our consent. For
all regular users currently existing, we set the Ubuntu Insights consent
according to this registry key, `0` being false, `1` being true. The
sources `linux`, and `wsl_setup` are set. Further consent steps are
skipped.

Finally, we fall back to asking the user interactively what they would
like to do. A short explanation as to what we are asking for is provided
and the user is provided an opportunity to view a sample report. The
answer `y` is prefilled. Once a choice is made, consent is set in the
same manner as with the registry key, and we also attempt to write the
registry key to save the answer to Windows.

### Initial report

After consent steps have been completed, and initial report via the
`wsl_setup` source is created. Since systemd is not guaranteed to be
available, we immediately attempt to upload the report. The allowed
source is narrowed down to `wsl_setup`, and the upload is done with
retry enabled. This is done in the background via a hidden subprocess,
allowing `wsl-setup` to exit even if an upload couldn't be achieved.

## Tests

The cloud-init based integration tests have been expanded, and a set of
interactive tests using `expect` have also been implemented within a
shared workflow.

To facilitate this, much of the validation logic has been refactored out
so that it can be easily reused. The implementation was done in such a
way such that certain parts can be disabled in case WSL 1 tests are ever
implemented.

For all tests, we kept all the existing assertions along with the
following:
- The internal `ubuntu-insights` `wsl_setup` consent state at the end is
what we expect for the default user
- The external Windows registry key value is what we expect
- One report has been created by `ubuntu-insights` for the source
`wsl_setup` for default user

## Notes

The `ubuntu-insights` script is executed instead of sourced as sourcing
it results in strange behaviors with `read` on GitHub runners, breaking
integration tests. The prompt doesn't get printed so `expect` can't
`expect` it directly, and sending any control characters such as Ctrl+U
and backspace causes the script to break. Sourcing works fine if expect
is ran locally, so it might be an issue with the runners using a dumb
terminal.

The implementation might be considered a breaking behavior for certain
automation workflows, as we are potentially introducing a new step in
the interactive process. Thus, the changelog is being incremented by a
minor version.

commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.

commits.author: adombeck
commits.message:
Improvements to e2e tests (#752)

* Support specifying the Ubuntu release to test. Currently supported:
questing and noble.
* Support `--rerunfailed` to only re-run the test cases which failed in
the previous test run. That's very useful when running the test cases
locally. This required two substantial changes:
* Making the test cases not rely on other test cases. Robot framework
expects test cases to be self-contained and to use setup and teardown
keywords to ensure they can all run from the same clean state.
`--rerunfailed` doesn't support running the full test suite which
failed, it only reruns those test cases which failed, so it causes
failures if those test cases depend on previous test cases.
* Calling `robot` directly instead of `yarf`. YARF runs the tests via
[`TestSuite.run`](https://robot-framework.readthedocs.io/en/latest/autodoc/robot.running.html#robot.running.model.TestSuite.run)
which does support passing options to it, but:
> Only options related to the actual test execution have an effect. For
example, options related to selecting or modifying test cases or suites
(e.g. --include, --name, --prerunmodifier) or creating logs and reports
are silently ignored.
So options like `--rerunfailed` don't have an effect. Fortunately, it's
simple to just use the keywords provided by YARF and execute tests
directly via the robot framework executable `robot`, which allows us to
use all its options.
* Stream the VM's systemd journal to the host and add it to the HTML log
* Many robustness improvements

commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
feat: Ubuntu Insights integration (#33)

This PR implements Ubuntu Insights integration with `wsl-setup` and
introduces a number of workflow tests along with it.

## Implementation
All steps are done at the end of the `wsl-setup` script, meaning that
cloud-init and users creation would have already been completed.

`ubuntu-insights` is added as a recommended dependency. If the CLI tool
can't be found, then we skip all following integration sections.

### Consent
Next, we check if at least one non-root user already has the *wsl_setup*
consent configuration set to a valid value. This could be done via
cloud-init or any other method of creating files and running commands.
If there is one, then we also skip all further consent steps.

Next, we utilize interop to check the registry key
`HKCU:\Software\Canonical\Ubuntu` value `UbuntuInsightsConsent`. If it
exists and is valid, either 0 or 1, then we use that as our consent. For
all regular users currently existing, we set the Ubuntu Insights consent
according to this registry key, `0` being false, `1` being true. The
sources `linux`, and `wsl_setup` are set. Further consent steps are
skipped.

Finally, we fall back to asking the user interactively what they would
like to do. A short explanation as to what we are asking for is provided
and the user is provided an opportunity to view a sample report. The
answer `y` is prefilled. Once a choice is made, consent is set in the
same manner as with the registry key, and we also attempt to write the
registry key to save the answer to Windows.

### Initial report

After consent steps have been completed, and initial report via the
`wsl_setup` source is created. Since systemd is not guaranteed to be
available, we immediately attempt to upload the report. The allowed
source is narrowed down to `wsl_setup`, and the upload is done with
retry enabled. This is done in the background via a hidden subprocess,
allowing `wsl-setup` to exit even if an upload couldn't be achieved.

## Tests

The cloud-init based integration tests have been expanded, and a set of
interactive tests using `expect` have also been implemented within a
shared workflow.

To facilitate this, much of the validation logic has been refactored out
so that it can be easily reused. The implementation was done in such a
way such that certain parts can be disabled in case WSL 1 tests are ever
implemented.

For all tests, we kept all the existing assertions along with the
following:
- The internal `ubuntu-insights` `wsl_setup` consent state at the end is
what we expect for the default user
- The external Windows registry key value is what we expect
- One report has been created by `ubuntu-insights` for the source
`wsl_setup` for default user

## Notes

The `ubuntu-insights` script is executed instead of sourced as sourcing
it results in strange behaviors with `read` on GitHub runners, breaking
integration tests. The prompt doesn't get printed so `expect` can't
`expect` it directly, and sending any control characters such as Ctrl+U
and backspace causes the script to break. Sourcing works fine if expect
is ran locally, so it might be an issue with the runners using a dumb
terminal.

The implementation might be considered a breaking behavior for certain
automation workflows, as we are potentially introducing a new step in
the interactive process. Thus, the changelog is being incremented by a
minor version.

commits.author: Kat
commits.message:
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support  (#89)

Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management
introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able
to parse any tools to install.

Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a
`.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the
case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed.

Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to
look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false
positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we
ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations.

Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example
`protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go`
as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two
such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool
should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't
trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as
a tool.

commits.author: Sergio Costas
commits.message:
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155)

Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed
to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a
function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters,
while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with
`(void)`.

This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has
been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a
compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these
functions.
